## 15. Key Evaluation Acronyms & Frameworks

### PEEL Structure (Use for EVERY AO3 point)

| Letter | Action | Example |
|--------|--------|---------|
| **P** — Point | State a clear strength or limitation | "A strength is that there is supporting research evidence." |
| **E** — Evidence | Cite supporting or contradicting research, or explain the logical basis | "Gottesman & Shields (1972) found a concordance rate of 58% in MZ twins compared to 12% in DZ twins." |
| **E** — Explain | Explain WHY this evidence supports or challenges the theory | "This supports the genetic explanation because MZ twins share 100% of their genes, so the higher concordance rate suggests genetics play a significant role." |
| **L** — Link | Link back to the question/theory | "Therefore, there is strong evidence to suggest that schizophrenia has a genetic basis." |

> **CRITICAL RULE: Every evaluation point MUST be contextualised to the specific study/theory in the question. NEVER write generic evaluation. See the templates below — you MUST fill in the [brackets] with the actual study/theory from the question, not leave them abstract.**

### Common Evaluation Points (contextualise every one)

| Evaluation Type | How to Use |
|----------------|------------|
| **Supporting research** | "A strength is that [study] found [findings], which supports [theory] because..." |
| **Contradicting research** | "A limitation is that [study] found [findings], which challenges [theory] because..." |
| **Ecological validity** | "A limitation is that [study] was conducted in [specific setting] using [specific task], which lacks ecological validity because [explain why this specific task/setting doesn't reflect real life for THIS topic]..." |
| **Population validity** | "A limitation is that [study] only used [specific sample e.g. American university students], so the findings cannot be generalised to [specific wider population] because [explain specific cultural/age/gender difference]..." |
| **Practical applications** | "A strength is that [theory] has led to [specific therapy/intervention e.g. CBT, SSRIs], which demonstrates its real-world value because [explain specific outcome]..." |
| **Determinism vs Free will** | "A limitation is that [theory] is deterministic because it suggests [specific behaviour] is caused by [specific factor], ignoring the role of free will..." |
| **Reductionism** | "A limitation is that [theory] is reductionist as it reduces [specific complex behaviour] to [specific single factor], ignoring other influences such as [name specific alternative factors]..." |
| **Nature vs Nurture** | "The [approach] takes a [nature/nurture] position, arguing that [specific behaviour] is primarily influenced by [genes/environment]..." |
| **Ethical issues** | "A limitation is that [specific study] raises ethical concerns regarding [specific issue e.g. deception in Milgram's study] because [explain specific harm/rights violation]..." |
| **Reliability** | "A strength is that [specific study] used [specific standardised procedure], making the findings more reliable because [explain why replicability matters for THIS topic]..." |

