## 16. General Exam Technique Rules

### Universal Rules

- **Always use psychological terminology** — e.g., "ecological validity" not "it's not realistic"
- **Always name researchers and dates** when citing studies — e.g., "Loftus & Palmer (1974)"
- **Never write generic evaluation** — always link evaluation points to the specific theory/study in the question
- **Application (AO2) must create explanatory links** — do NOT just repeat the stem; explain WHY it fits the theory
- **Balance strengths and limitations** in evaluation — don't only criticise or only praise
- **Answer the exact question** — if it says "discuss," you need AO1 AND AO3; if it says "outline," focus on AO1; if it says "evaluate," focus on AO3

### Levels of Response Mark Bands

| Level | 8-mark | 12-mark | 16-mark | Description |
|-------|--------|---------|---------|-------------|
| **4 (Top)** | 7–8 | 10–12 | 13–16 | Detailed, accurate AO1. Effective evaluation with elaboration. Coherent, focused answer |
| **3** | 5–6 | 7–9 | 9–12 | Mostly detailed AO1. Some effective evaluation. Mostly coherent |
| **2** | 3–4 | 4–6 | 5–8 | Limited AO1. Basic evaluation, lacks elaboration. May lack coherence |
| **1** | 1–2 | 1–3 | 1–4 | Very limited AO1. Superficial evaluation. Poorly organised |
| **0** | 0 | 0 | 0 | No relevant content |

### What Separates Level 3 from Level 4

| Level 3 | Level 4 |
|---------|---------|
| Evaluation is present but not fully elaborated | Evaluation is effective — elaborated with evidence AND linked back |
| Application may quote the stem without explaining why | Application creates explanatory links between theory and scenario |
| Key terms may be used but not consistently | Key terms used confidently throughout |
| Structure may wander | Structure is coherent and focused — clear line of argument |
| May describe evaluation rather than analyse | Evaluation points clearly explain why something is a strength/limitation |

